Smokers are at greater risk of losing teeth
Smoking not only damages the lungs but also the teeth, suggests a long-term study in Potsdam.
The good news is, if you give up, the risk drops quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is shown by the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Smokers were 2.5 to 3.6 times more likely to lose their teeth prematurely than non-smokers.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth decay are caries and inflammation of the gums, stresses the DIfE.
For this periodontitis, the authors stress that smoking is a risk factor.
The association between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to higher incidence of gum disease in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of cavities.
However, people who quit smoking may reduce their risk in a short time, write the researchers in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it may take more than ten years for the risk to return to the level of nonsmokers, explained lead author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham in England.
"Smoking shortens life", explained study leader Heiner Boeing of DIfE, "if people are to be persuaded to become nonsmokers".
Not smoking is good for the lungs and blood vessels, and we know that it also promotes good dental health into old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE reported.
Previous studies have suggested that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
