The pound rises as UK wages grow faster
The pound rose sharply on data indicating an increase in UK wage growth, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the SABMiller bid target.
Between May and July, profit without bonus in the United Kingdom grew by 2.9% compared with the same period of the previous year.
This percentage was the fastest since 2009 and the most accurate estimate of the timing of an interest rate increase.
The pound rose by more than 1% against the dollar to $1,5505 and climbed to €1,3730 against the euro by 0.84%.
The FTSE 100 index closed with an increase of 1.49% to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the dominant share on the market, rising by 20% following the takeover bid by rival AB InBev.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were up 0.9% following encouraging news from rival luxury goods group Richemont.
Richemont's latest sales figures beat all expectations and also showed that sales in China - a key market for Burberry - are again reporting growth.
Glencore's stock rose 5 percent after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5 billion through a stock sale as part of its debt-reduction strategy.
The shares of the packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, falling by 4.3%, after Goldman Sachs had set its rating for the company at 'sell'.
JD Sports increased by 3,1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax profit of 46,6 million for the six months.
The head of JD Sports says higher wages are a threat to expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says that a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean "more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers".
But he says it is unlikely that this purchasing power will compensate for the higher labor costs at his company.
The cost could meet JD Sports' expansion plans, he added, and that could mean fewer additional jobs.
