Metcash launches ground stability campaign to combat Aldi
Metcash is trying to protect IGA branches from an Aldi rally in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-breaking campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in the run-up to a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centres and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide Show.
IGA dealers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands like Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo, which distributes samples to IGA stores, and shop owners selling discounted South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defence strategy on 29 September when the wholesaler of food, alcohol and equipment conducts its annual Investor Strategy Day.
The stakes are high, as South Australia and Western Australia account for almost 30% of Metcash's IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the Eastern States.
Shoppers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30% in South Australia and 24% in Western Australia compared to around 14% in the Eastern States.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that within 12 months of opening its first markets, Aldi will grab around 5% of the food market in these two states and will take sales away from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in South Africa and 30 in WA next year, with sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and beverage business and in the volumes on Metcash's high fixed cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern States, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley assumes that Metcash's sales in the food and beverage business will fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and by 2.1 percent in 2018, and will reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, the chief fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to comment publicly on Mr. Douglass's comments.
But it is believed that a board member of Metcash made contact with Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18% to 14% since 2010, and revenue from Metcash's food and grocery business, which serves some 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43% since 2012, reflecting operational debt relief while putting pressure on sales and margins.
But the wholesaler is fighting back, investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores with faster growing fresh food and providing a better choice of private label food.
Metcash's CEO Ian Morrice says that price adjustments and store renovation programs will be attributed to Elan and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profitable growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by Australian Tennis Federation President Steve Healy
