Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to Australian Tennis Association president Steve Healy, deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, who are often referred to as "Special Ks", came to the limelight after Kyrgios' infamous confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison shouting, "Wawrinka should have hit Kyrgios, and I should have hit the kid".
While last seen crushing a tennis bat after a cramp thwarted a potential US Open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm pretty proud of is the fact that I think Thanasi got a little bit dragged into the fight", Healy said.
He broke a bat when he lost the U.S. Open to a cramp, but he's not the first player to break a bat out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he did extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around him, and I think he's been treated a little too harshly.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits in the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the dressing room, he trains hard, he's in good shape, he's a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision to disregard Kyrgios in the important preliminary decision starting on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the Canberra man to return as a long-term fixture on the team".
"First, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios]", Healy said.
And I think Nick has made the rise very quickly that people like Federer and Murray have pointed out, he's rising in the public eye, and he's made some bad mistakes and he deserves all the criticism he gets, but we're trying to support him, we're trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions, some time out of the limelight where he can just think about it, I think is appropriate, and it's best for the team and it's best for him.
