Hungary declared a state of emergency and sealed its southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining anyone trying to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the flow of migrants.
Chaos ensued at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man's land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries, and they built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults at the Hungarian emergency police.
Some rejected food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants were being sent back from Hungary while more and more are arriving from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days", said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree on a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
