The Fed has a twofold mandate from Congress: maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-factor in a decision that's too narrow to predict, and it's going to be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start, to be weaned off the unprecedented stimulus from the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Although most data on the economy shows that it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could make already cautious Fed officials fearful of increasing this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds - even by a quarter of a percentage point.
