But financial markets around the world contracted late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell more than 16% below its peak in May as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below its May high.
For Fed officials, market turbulence influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
"If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy hadn't occurred over the past few weeks, they would have pulled the plug at this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the US Federal Reserve.
Now he predicts she'll wait at least a month to better handle the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China", Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the Fed's primary concerns, so it should not be technically included in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere mention by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "squeeze" its monetary expansion caused confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreacting to financial market movements that are apparently not tied to the economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee who advocates an interest rate increase, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions "despite limited discernible effects on U.S. growth", Lacker said.
