For people with mildly overweight diabetes, weight-loss surgery may be helpful.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly overweight people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is too early to say whether mildly obese people with diabetes will live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatments.
"The mortality data take a long time to show anything", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight-loss surgery who wrote an editorial on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgery, or obesity surgery, uses various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, obesity surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been done on people who are morbidly obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight in relation to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI of over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data they had collected in a study since 2007 to compare two types of obesity surgery - gastric bypass and gastric bypass - to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were slightly overweight.
The average BMI of those who underwent this surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, BMI remained about the same at 29 for those receiving nonsurgical diabetes treatments.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% had completely and 28% had partially resolved their diabetes.
In the medically treated group, only about one percent of the patients had complete and partial diabetes, compared with about two percent.
In addition, results on blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the 'surgical' group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The best way to keep hemoglobin A1c below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After the surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medically treated group, it remained stable at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" - as reflected in improved hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce mortality within five years, said lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results for the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, the bypass surgery group had lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg) compared with the gastrectomy group, achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 vs. 2.1%) and were more likely to have completely overcome diabetes (46.9 vs. 16.7%).
While the new study shows no survival benefit after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavier people in Sweden that surgery leads to longer lives, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona, College of Medicine Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had obesity surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die over the course of 15 years than a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study showed no benefit for survival in the surgery patients, Blackstone said it was reassuring for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in the procedure.
"That's the critical point of this study, because it says that this surgery is lower in this lower BMI group", without increased risk of death or kidney disease, she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we're waiting too long to get people to take this seriously", she said.
I think once they've accumulated those genetic changes that have tied their bodies to obesity and diabetes, it's really hard to reverse".
