Quadrupling of children's hand sanitizer intake in the last four years
Poison control centers in the United States report a nearly 400-percent increase in children under the age of 12 who swallow strongly alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, the number of children under 12 who used hand sanitizers, as reported by poison control centers, rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are getting more and more of these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them end up in the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink disinfectants on purpose, while others do it to impress their friends or because of a social media test.
Videos on YouTube show how teenagers drink disinfectants just for a cheap experience.
Teenagers reportedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to make a tougher drink.
Younger children may be attracted by the attractive scents of disinfectants.
"A child doesn't think this is bad for him", Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with the scent of strawberries, grapes and oranges that are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizers contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, even a few syringes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol", Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison emergency center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Now, you wouldn't leave a sip of whiskey standing around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and when children get to it, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four syringes of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice the legal drinking level for an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah listened to her words and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma, as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and hit her head, Ritchey said.
"It was very scary", Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal to my child.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use alcohol-free products or disinfectant wipes and store hand sanitizers out of the child's reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizers that contained a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspected that the product contained methanol, a lethal solution, instead of the ethyl alcohol listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-graders in New York State planned to poison their "ordinary" teacher by placing antibacterial products around the classroom", reports a police report.
The teacher is highly allergic to hand sanitizers and banished her from her room.
The police considered the foiled plan "gossip" and referred disciplinary action to the school board.
