He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who will also meet with representatives of industry at the IAA.
The Ministry of Transport's strategy paper stresses, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid shift to digital radio.
A test track is currently being built on the Bavarian motorway 9 to test new technology.
In order to avoid "additional liability risks" for the driver, the Federal Government intends to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to new developments".
For example, Germany is seeking to promote the international increase of the maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to work for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for human drivers.
In automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver becoming more and more the passenger.
The technology is based primarily on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads "are not expected until well after 2020".
The value added in the area of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the German site is estimated by the authors of the study to be around EUR 8.4 billion in 2025.
"Digital car networking can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road traffic", said Sören Bartol, SPD transport policy-maker.
The question of liability in the event of accidents and the security of the personal data of drivers must be clearly clarified.
Yet, Germans are still skeptical of self-driving cars - far more so than Frenchmen or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute, commissioned by the research organization Dekra, and presented on Wednesday at the AA, concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect it in 20 years, and 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect self-driving cars by 2025, in the United States, 33 percent.
In any case, the drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to hand over control of all roads during the entire journey.
On the highway, you could imagine 15 percent in traffic, 45 percent in traffic jams.
One in four would never give up control of the car under any circumstances.
