Gaultier feels too old for a terrible child
It is a mixture of a very large fashion show and a wax figure-gruselka cabinet: Designer Jean Paul Gaultier (63) presented an exhibition of his work in Munich on Wednesday.
Highlights: Dolls that appear terrifyingly human through video projections.
They're wearing the spectacular creations of the French designer, who became a major star in the fashion world with Madonna's stage outfits - and with putting men in skirts.
"I can't say I'm the Enfant terrible of haute couture anymore because I have white hair".
"It used to be bleached, but now it's real", said Gaultier.
For visitors to the exhibition "From The Sidewalk To The Catwalk", which will be on view at the Hypo Culture Foundation's Art Hall from 18 September, it is a good thing that the fashion designer has changed his initial attitude from one of rejection to one of self-expression.
He was actually against it, because, he said, "An exhibition sounded a little bit like death to me".
When you die, you go to the museum.
The impressive collection had previously made stops in Montreal, Canada, and Paris.
"It's so much more than just beautiful dresses", said the art gallery's director, Roger Diederen.
It's about tolerance, acceptance and the vision of an open society.
The exhibits give a glimpse into the hardly-exhaustible work of the man who wrote fashion history without ever having completed an education.
The show is not chronologically structured, but it is a perfectly choreographed work of art for which a great deal of effort has been put in: for example, a stylist was hired to do the dolls.
14 tons of material were transported to Munich by the makers, according to curator Thierry-Maxime Loriot.
Just before the start of the Oktoberfest, there was a special costume: a leather trouser outfit with corset.
Heidi is meeting Madonna.
He's always been interested in strong women ("women are smarter than men") and people who are a little different, Gaultier said.
Gaultier's old Teddy is on display, too.
It represents the designer's first tentative fashion attempts.
As a child (he wasn't a good student and bad at football), he wore his Teddy B-Shirts and dresses, Gaultier said.
His parents wouldn't have let him play with a doll.
He later taught himself how to design fashion.
He stole fashion magazines and looked at other designers' designs, as Gaultier told us in Munich.
But of course, I bought them later.
He couldn't afford the models for his first fashion show.
They didn't get anything, but they could keep the clothes.
Jewelry instead of curtains - Plain top as a fashion niche
In the old days, the long knitting machines were all about making meters.
The embroidered fabrics and spikes were produced in large quantities for customers, who processed them into, for example, ceilings and curtains.
This alone is no longer possible, explains Andreas Reinhardt, managing director of the fashion spike Plauen.
Instead, fashion is important again.
In the early days of the Plauener Spitze, fashion played a bigger role, then was supplanted by the home textile industry - and is now being rediscovered as a niche.
Reinhardt gives some examples: top-notch jewelry, accessories such as bags and regional costumes.
In general, the so-called vintage fashion, which is based on past styles, is creating an increasing potential for orders.
If you are not in the textile industry in Germany, you are no longer on the market.
They're already half of our orders.
Modespitze Plauen is a member of the trade association Plauener Spitze und Embroidery together with nine other companies.
Only they can wear the protected label.
In the last 15 years, about 80 percent of the sales have been lost.
Private specialist shops and wholesale trade are almost gone.
Our products hardly reach the customer this way anymore.
The bulk goods are now produced much cheaper in Asia and sold almost exclusively through chains.
Exports to Russia and the United States are also weakening.
So, enough reason to go new ways.
The industry association also tries to score by environmental awareness, as Cordula Bauer from Stickperle in Falkenstein explains: "Since this year we have a quality label which shows that we produce in an ecologically and socially sustainable way".
Reinhardt adds: "This also applies to the materials used".
The graduate designer Ute Schmidt teaches at the Schneeberger branch of the West Saxony University of Applied Arts in Zwickau, and specializes in embroidery and spikes.
To compete with the Asian market, you have to find high-quality and innovative products.
It takes time and courage.
A tension is created between the freshest ideas of designers and companies that must think economically first", says Schmidt.
Therefore, an existing design is often only slightly modified to keep a customer base.
A few years ago, textile designer Kati Reuter revived the historic snowball top.
The machine stitches small balls in some places.
The Plauen goldsmith Bianca Hallebach-Krauße was inspired by this: "Before, I could do nothing with traditional Plauen spikes".
Now she uses the snowball tip for her jewelry.
In an elaborate process, she embroidered the pattern in silver.
"Many people in the region identify with the theme of Plauener Spitze - young and old", says Reuter.
It also delivers to the USA, Australia and Finland - mainly to customers whose ancestors lived in and around Plauen and who want a souvenir.
I see my jewelry as a modern ambassador of the Plauen peak.
