Xi urges opening up the economy to the world
The economy must open up more broadly to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering reform on Tuesday.
"China should strive to attract foreign investment and know-how and improve business start-up strategies", he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group on Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Fostering innovation and pushing for reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and open up new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Leadership Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list on market access, relaxation of border control policies, promotion of SOEs, private capital and overhaul of the resident reporting system.
The statement will be followed by a negative list identifying sectors and enterprises not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by means of test programmes.
The initiative is important as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a rule of law business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also relax controls over the powers conferred on enterprises and ensure that enterprises decide how to conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should be able to make a decision on the financing of the project.
"The government will not change its foreign investment policy and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded enterprises and provide better services to them", the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the Green Card by streamlining the requirements and simplifying the application process.
The right to guarantee lawyers the right to practise their profession and to employ professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at a meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement released after the meeting.
EU to double mercury limit in predatory fisheries
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby providing consumers with a much higher dose of the nerve agent.
The EU consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a working paper on the matter, sharply criticised the plans: "Risks and side effects of poor industrial and environmental policies are being passed on with full force to pregnant women and young children", explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
Wolfschmidt said that the limit values for nerve toxin for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as sharks and swordfish, should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should take the necessary measures to ensure that the fisheries sector is not affected by the current situation.
After doubling the thresholds, only 14.5 percent would remain unsold.
In return for this relaxation, Foodwatch says the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller fish, such as carp, are usually so low in load that they already meet the planned maximum levels.
The reduction in small-scale fisheries is therefore "a perfidious diversionary maneuver which only helps the economy", Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal to humans, which is highly enriched in the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The Federal Government therefore warns that "even small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the unborn".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment states on its website that, with regard to the maximum values in force, a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the combustion of coal.
According to a written report from the Federal Environment Ministry to the Green Party Member of Parliament, Annalena Baerbock, German coal-fired power stations emit more than six tonnes of mercury a year, two thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany.
The mercury concentration in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and extensively exceeded", the newspaper Spiegel quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, European-wide warnings for mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
